Linear SVM is used when the dataset is linearly separable, meaning the classes can be separated by drawing a straight line (in two dimensions) or a flat plane (in higher dimensions). The algorithm identifies the optimal hyperplane that maximizes the margin between different classes. Linear SVM is computationally efficient and performs well on datasets with clear class boundaries.

Examples
	• Email Spam Detection 
	• Pass / Fail Prediction 
	• Disease Diagnosis 
	• Loan Approval 

Nonlinear SVM
Nonlinear SVM is used when the dataset cannot be separated by a straight line or plane. It uses kernel functions to transform the data into a higher-dimensional space, where it becomes easier to separate the classes. Common kernels include the Polynomial Kernel, Radial Basis Function (RBF) Kernel, and Sigmoid Kernel. This allows SVM to solve complex classification problems.
