Important Components of SVM

 Hyperplane
A hyperplane is the decision boundary that separates different classes in an SVM model. In two-dimensional space, it is a straight line, while in higher dimensions it becomes a flat plane or surface. The objective of SVM is to find the hyperplane that best separates the classes with the maximum margin.
Example
Suppose we have two classes:
	• Class A = Circles 
	• Class B = Squares 
A straight line separating the two classes is called the hyperplane.

Support Vectors
Definition
Support vectors are the data points that lie closest to the hyperplane. These points are the most important observations because they determine the position and orientation of the hyperplane. If the support vectors change, the hyperplane also changes.
Example
In a spam detection dataset, the emails that are closest to the decision boundary become the support vectors.

3.3 Margin
Definition
The margin is the distance between the hyperplane and the nearest support vectors from each class. SVM always tries to maximize this margin because a larger margin generally leads to better classification performance and improved generalization on unseen data.
Example
A larger gap between the two classes results in a more reliable classifier.

4. Kernel Functions
Kernel functions enable SVM to solve nonlinear classification problems by transforming the data into a higher-dimensional space.
Types of Kernels
Kernel	Description	Example
Linear Kernel	Used for linearly separable data	Text Classification
Polynomial Kernel	Creates curved decision boundaries	Image Classification
RBF (Gaussian) Kernel	Most commonly used for nonlinear data	Face Recognition
Sigmoid Kernel	Similar to neural network activation	Pattern Recognition

