5. Working of SVM
Step 1: Collect the Dataset
Prepare the labeled training dataset.
Example
Age	Income	Loan
25	30000	Rejected
35	60000	Approved
45	80000	Approved

Step 2: Select Features
Choose the input features that will be used for classification.
Example:
	• Age 
	• Income 

Step 3: Find the Optimal Hyperplane
The algorithm searches for the hyperplane that best separates the classes while maximizing the margin.

Step 4: Identify Support Vectors
The data points nearest to the hyperplane are selected as support vectors.

Step 5: Classify New Data
A new observation is placed on one side of the hyperplane, and the algorithm predicts its class.

Example
A bank wants to predict whether a loan should be approved.
Training Data
Credit Score	Loan Status
720	Approved
680	Approved
520	Rejected
490	Rejected
New Customer
	• Credit Score = 700 
Since the score lies on the Approved side of the hyperplane,
Prediction = Loan Approved

Advantages
	• High accuracy for classification tasks. 
	• Effective for high-dimensional datasets. 
	• Performs well with small and medium-sized datasets. 
	• Resistant to overfitting due to maximum margin optimization. 
	• Supports both linear and nonlinear classification.
